{"altmetric_id":15988652,"counts":{"readers":{"mendeley":2,"citeulike":0,"connotea":0},"total":{"posts_count":3},"twitter":{"unique_users_count":2,"unique_users":["memoalexlope","ORRCHIDRAIN"],"posts_count":2},"facebook":{"unique_users_count":1,"unique_users":["215019301963281"],"posts_count":1}},"selected_quotes":["Pseudomicetoma dermatof\u00edtico en cuero cabelludo"],"citation":{"abstract":"Dermatophytic pseudomycetoma represents a chronic infection characterized by a tumor-like growth containing dermatophytes arranged as clustered aggregates (grains) within the dermis. In contrast to mycetomas, they lack sinus tracts and are more common in the scalp. We describe a dermatophytic pseudomycetoma arising in the scalp of an 18-year-old African-American woman. Histopathologic examination showed a dense, mixed-cell infiltrate expanding the dermis. Accompanying this infiltrate were numerous grains scattered throughout the dermis. No sinus tracts were identified, but a number of grains were seen in the epidermal surface, admixed with serum crust. Recognition of a dermatophytic infection as a pseudomycetoma on a biopsy is important, as surgery may be required for a successful treatment.","altmetric_jid":"4f6fa6083cf058f610006970","authors":["Castro-Echeverry, Eduardo","Fiala, Katherine","Fernandez, Martin P."],"doi":"10.1097\/dad.0000000000000702","first_seen_on":"2017-01-31T14:20:41+00:00","funders":["niehs"],"issns":["0193-1091","1533-0311"],"issue":"2","journal":"The American Journal of Dermatopathology","last_mentioned_on":1485872659,"links":["http:\/\/journals.lww.com\/amjdermatopathology\/Abstract\/2017\/02000\/Dermatophytic_Pseudomycetoma_of_the_Scalp.21.aspx"],"pdf_url":"http:\/\/pdfs.journals.lww.com\/amjdermatopathology\/2017\/02000\/Dermatophytic_Pseudomycetoma_of_the_Scalp.21.pdf","pmid":"28134737","pubdate":"2017-02-01T00:00:00+00:00","publisher":"LWW","publisher_subjects":[{"name":"Clinical Sciences","scheme":"era"}],"scopus_subjects":["Medicine","Health Sci